# Webview & RPC (src/webview/**)

The webview is a **sandboxed browser context** loaded into a
`vscode.WebviewPanel`. It has no Node, no `fs`, and no direct VS Code API.
Everything dynamic flows through RPC over `postMessage`.

## Rendering: Preact + htm only

Use the tagged-template renderer in
[@src/webview/render.ts](mdc:src/webview/render.ts). Never write to
`innerHTML`, `outerHTML`, `document.write`, or `insertAdjacentHTML`. ESLint
catches the obvious cases; this rule covers the subtle ones.

```ts
import { html, render } from './render';
import { StatCard, CanvasEl } from './render';

function MyCard({ value, label }: { value: string; label: string }) {
  return html`<div class="card"><b>${value}</b> ${label}</div>`;
}

render(html`<${MyCard} value=${42} label="requests" />`, container);
```

- **String interpolation in `html\`...\`` is auto-escaped.** That's why
  `${untrustedSessionPrompt}` is safe inside text nodes.
- For numbers / CSS class names / inline-style values that must round-trip
  through attributes, use the helpers in `./shared`:
  `safeNumber()`, `safeCssClass()`, `safeCssValue()`. Do **not** import
  `rawHtml` — ESLint discourages it and reviewers will reject it.
- Reusable building blocks (`StatCard`, `CanvasEl`, `ScoreRing`,
  `PctBadge`, `LoadingScreen`, `ErrorMsg`, `withErrorBoundary`) live in
  `render.ts`. Add new shared atoms there, not in page modules.
- Render **coaching copy** (rule descriptions / advice, config suggestions)
  through `mdInline` / `mdBlock` from
  [@src/webview/markdown.ts](mdc:src/webview/markdown.ts) so authored Markdown
  (inline `code`, `**bold**`, lists, links) renders formatted instead of
  leaking raw backticks into the UI. Never drop a rule/advice string into a
  template as a bare `${value}`. **Verbatim user data** (example rows, prompt
  previews, occurrence messages) stays plain — Markdown-rendering it would
  mangle a stray `*` or backtick the user actually typed.

## Page module pattern

Every top-level page exports `renderXxx(container, filter)`:

```ts
export async function renderMyPage(
  container: HTMLElement,
  filter: DateFilter,
): Promise<void> {
  const data = await rpc<MyShape>('getMyData', filter);
  render(html`...`, container);
}
```

- Wire the page into [@src/webview/app.ts](mdc:src/webview/app.ts) by
  adding an entry to the page dispatcher and importing it at the top.
- Wrap page renders with `withErrorBoundary(name, container, () => ...)` so
  a single page's failure does not nuke the whole panel.
- Keep page modules **render-only**. Business logic lives in
  `src/core/analyzer-*.ts` and is exposed via RPC.
- One page per file. Resist multi-page mega-modules.

## RPC contract

The webview ↔ host RPC has two halves:

1. **Pure analytics** — registered in
   [@src/webview/panel-rpc.ts](mdc:src/webview/panel-rpc.ts) (`getRpcHandler`).
   Signature is defined by `RpcMethodMap` in
   [@src/core/types/rpc-types.ts](mdc:src/core/types/rpc-types.ts) — add
   your method to that type first, then implement.
2. **Side-effectful or LLM-backed** — handled by
   [@src/webview/panel-request-service.ts](mdc:src/webview/panel-request-service.ts).
   Use this when you need to call `vscode.lm`, hit the filesystem, write a
   file, or open another VS Code surface.

To add an RPC method:

1. Add a typed entry to `RpcMethodMap` (and a matching `RpcResult` row if
   the return is non-trivial).
2. Implement the handler in `panel-rpc.ts` (or `panel-request-service.ts`
   for side-effectful) — validate every field of the incoming payload with
   the `isString` / `isNumber` / `isRecord` / `isOptionalString`
   typeguards from [@src/webview/panel-shared.ts](mdc:src/webview/panel-shared.ts).
   Treat the payload as `unknown` until you've narrowed it.
3. Call from the webview with `rpc<ReturnType>('methodName', payload)`
   (helper in `shared.ts`). Use `rpcAllSettled` when you fan out several
   independent requests for one page render.
4. **Trust nothing on either side.** Session text and tool results are
   untrusted user data — do not let them flow into the system prompt or
   into HTML without escaping.

## Charts

Charts use Chart.js via `createChart(id, config)` and are tracked by id.
**Always** call `destroyChartById(id)` (or rely on the page's
`destroyCharts()`) before re-creating a chart with the same id — leaks
otherwise stack up across filter changes.

## CSP and Trusted Types

`render.ts` installs a `default` Trusted Types policy so Preact's internal
SVG `innerHTML` assignments pass CSP. Do not install other policies, and
do not bypass CSP with `eval` or dynamic `Function` construction. If you
need to evaluate user-authored expressions, route them through the
DSL interpreter in [@src/core/dsl/](mdc:src/core/dsl/).

## State

There is intentionally **no global UI framework**. Page-level state lives
as module-level `let` in the page file (e.g. `activeMetric` in
`page-dashboard.ts`). Cross-page state goes through `app.ts` or
`skill-cache.ts`. Avoid global mutation outside these well-known spots.

## Filenames

- `panel-*.ts` — extension-host side of the webview (runs in Node).
- `page-*.ts` — webview-side renderers (runs in the browser sandbox).
- `render.ts` / `shared.ts` / `panel-shared.ts` — shared atoms.

Keep that split; it is also how esbuild splits bundles.

## Sync `.cursor/` when you change the webview

- New `page-*.ts` → add it to the page list in
  [@.cursor/context/architecture.md](mdc:.cursor/context/architecture.md)
  and add a matching docs page under
  [@docs/content/](mdc:docs/content/).
- New RPC method or change to `RpcMethodMap` →
  `architecture.md` has a *Webview RPC* section that describes the
  envelope and split between `panel-rpc.ts` / `panel-request-service.ts`;
  keep it accurate.
- Changed the rendering primitive (e.g. swapped Preact + htm for
  something else, added a different state pattern) → this rule's
  *Rendering* and *Page module pattern* sections need to change too.
  Don't leave the old guidance in place — it will get followed.
